This KQL query provides a high-level threat landscape overview by aggregating behavioral security signals across Microsoft Defender XDR and Microsoft Sentinel data sources. It analyzes entries in the BehaviorInfo table and summarizes threat‑related metadata such as action types, categories, MITRE attack techniques, sources, and detection origins.

By grouping and counting these behaviors, the query helps security teams quickly identify:

🔥 Which threat actions are happening most frequently
🧭 Which categories of behaviors are most active in the environment
🕒 When a suspicious or malicious behavior was first and last seen
🛰️ Where the signal came from (Cloud Apps, Sentinel,)
🎯 Relevant attack techniques and descriptions to understand attacker intent

This delivers an immediate snapshot of your current threat landscape and ongoing attacker activity.

🎯 How This Helps Your Security Team
1️⃣ Threat Landscape Awareness
The query provides a clear view of which malicious or suspicious behaviors are most common in your environment.
Instead of looking through raw logs, analysts get an aggregated map of real activity happening across devices, identities, email, and cloud workloads.

2️⃣ Faster Investigation & Triage
Because it pulls example descriptions and attack techniques, the team instantly sees:

What this behavior represents
Which MITRE techniques it aligns to
Whether it's related to credential abuse, lateral movement, persistence, exfiltration, etc.

This gives analysts immediate context without needing to dig through individual events.
3️⃣ Cross‑Source Correlation (XDR + Sentinel)
Your query includes ServiceSource and DetectionSource, letting analysts understand whether signals are coming from:


Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps
Sentinel Analytics Rules
Sentinel UEBA Behaviors

This makes it easier to spot multi-vector attacks and correlate suspicious actions across different security products.

4️⃣ Realistic Threat Scenarios
By showing first and last seen timestamps + attack technique examples, the query helps build realistic investigation scenarios:

Is this a one-time event or repeated behavior?
Is the attacker escalating?
Is this technique part of a broader kill chain?
Is this tactic common across affected devices or accounts?

This allows teams to understand how the attacker operates and what technique sequence is unfolding.

5️⃣ Prioritization Through Sorting
Sorting by ThreatCount (descending) highlights what’s happening the most — so the SOC focuses where it matters.

____________________________________________________________

BehaviorInfo
| where isnotempty(ActionType) and isnotempty(Categories)
| summarize
    ThreatCount = count(),
    FirstSeen = min(TimeGenerated),
    LastSeen = max(TimeGenerated),
    ExampleDescription = any(Description),
    ExampleAttackTechniques = any(AttackTechniques)
    by ActionType, tostring(Categories), ServiceSource, DetectionSource
| extend
    ThreatType = ActionType,
    ThreatCategory = tostring(Categories),
    Source = ServiceSource,
    Detection = DetectionSource
| project
    ThreatType,
    ThreatCategory,
    ThreatCount,
    FirstSeen,
    LastSeen,
    Source,
    Detection,
    ExampleAttackTechniques,
    ExampleDescription
| sort by ThreatCount desc
